stock market liberalization economic reform and emerging market equity prices siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display stock market liberalization economic reform and emerging market equity prices type siepr discussion paper 496 author s peter henry published 09 1 97 download pdf abstract the decade from 1984 to 1994 witnessed unprecedented emerging stock market liberalizations as governments from caracas to kuala lumpur opened their equity markets to non residents for the first time emerging market stock prices also boomed during this period it is tempting to conclude that the stock market openings were responsible for the jump in asset prices but the wave of openings was concurrent with a period of drastic economic reform what then caused the boom was it external opening reform or both by constructing an exhaustive list of all major stock market liberalizations and economic reforms occurring in twelve ldcs from 1984 to 1994 i am able to disentangle the effects of stock market opening from the influence of economic reform the results are striking the effects of stock market liberalization are at most two thirds as large as suggested by previous work and economic reforms are an equally important source of asset revaluation stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
